  "response": "The scanner flags `src/assets/check-icon.png` as an **Icon-Sized Raster** (`crime_00014`, low severity, confidence 0.85) with these dimensions, quoted verbatim:\n\n> \"dimensions: 32 × 32 px (≤ 64 threshold both sides)\"\n\nWhy a new SVG indicator beats another 32×32 PNG at those dimensions:\n\n- **DPI lock-in.** A 32×32 PNG renders cleanly only at 1× density. On a 2× or 3× display (every modern laptop and phone), the browser upscales 32 px of source into 64 or 96 device pixels and the icon looks soft. You'd need to ship `@2x` and `@3x` variants — three assets instead of one — to keep parity. SVG renders sharp at every DPI from a single file.\n- **No headroom for size changes.** The moment design wants the status indicator at 20 px in a dense table and 40 px in an empty state, the 32 px raster is wrong in both places. SVG scales to whatever the layout asks for without re-exporting.\n- **Bytes.** The scanner's own remediation note on this finding — \"same render at every DPI, smaller bytes\" — applies here too: a single-glyph status indicator as SVG is typically a few hundred bytes of path data, smaller than a PNG at 32×32 plus its retina variants combined.\n- **Themability.** SVG paths can inherit `currentColor`, so one file covers light/dark mode and any state color (success green, warning amber, etc.). A PNG locks color into the pixels.\n\nThe cheapest move is to author the new indicator as an inline or imported SVG from the start — and the same scanner finding is an open invitation to replace `check-icon.png` next time it's touched.",
